## RecursiveCharacterTextSplitter `Default`

```note
┌─────────────────────┐        ┌──────────────────────────────┐        ┌─────────────────────┐
│      Document       │        │        Splitter Config       │        │       Chunks        │
│                     │        │                              │        │                     │
│  Paragraph 1...     │        │  chunk_size                  │        │  ┌───────────────┐  │
│  \n\n               │  ───►  │    1000                      │  ───►  │  │    Chunk 1    │  │
│  Paragraph 2...     │        │                              │        │  └───────┬───────┘  │
│  \n                 │        │  chunk_overlap               │        │        overlap      │
│  Line 3...          │        │    200                       │        │  ┌───────▼───────┐  │
│  Words...           │        │                              │        │  │    Chunk 2    │  │
│                     │        │  separators                  │        │  └───────┬───────┘  │
│                     │        │  ["\n\n", "\n", " "]         │        │        overlap      │
│                     │        │                              │        │  ┌───────▼───────┐  │
│                     │        │                              │        │  │    Chunk 3    │  │
│                     │        │                              │        │  └───────────────┘  │
└─────────────────────┘        └──────────────────────────────┘        └─────────────────────┘
```

- RecursiveCharacterTextSplitter 只有在**無法**透過目前的 Separator 將文字切分成**符合 chunk_size 的 Chunk** 時，才會繼續使用下一層 Separator 遞迴切割；此時才可能套用 **chunk_overlap**。
- 如果透過適當的分隔符（例如 \n\n、\n 或空格）就能切出小於 chunk_size 的 Chunk，則會直接以該分隔點切割，不會因為設定了 chunk_overlap 而刻意加入重疊內容。

---

### Split Priority

> Tries paragraph breaks first, then lines, then spaces, then characters.

| Priority | Separator | Represents        |
|----------|-----------|-------------------|
| 1st      | `\n\n`    | Paragraph breaks  |
| 2nd      | `\n`      | Line breaks       |
| 3rd      | `" "`     | Spaces            |
| 4th      | `""`      | Characters        |

---

### Chunk Size Guidelines

| Use Case          | Chunk Size    | Overlap   | Why       |
|-------------------|---------------|-----------|-----------|
| Q&A / FAQ         | 500 - 800     | 50 - 100  | Precision |
| Documentation     | 1000 - 1500   | 200       | Context   |
| Code              | 1500 - 2000   | 200       | Functions |
| Books / Articles  | 800 - 1200    | 150       | Balance   |


#### Chunk Size Scale

| Too Small | Optimal | Too Large |
|-----------|---------|-----------|
| ◄─────────|─────────|─────────► |

---

RFI (Request for Information) and RFP (Request for Proposal) documents often have a **Q&A** or **requirements-list** structure, so the FAQ chunking strategy (500–800 tokens, 50–100 overlap) is generally the right starting point. Each question/requirement is discrete and self-contained, so smaller chunks help the retriever return the precise answer to a specific question.

However, RFPs in particular can blur the line depending on the section. For example:

- **Q&A / requirements sections** → chunk as FAQ (500–800 tokens). Precise retrieval of specific answers.
- **Scope of work or technical approach sections** → these are more narrative and interconnected, so bumping up closer to the Documentation range (1000–1500 tokens) may work better.
- **Compliance or legal sections** → similar to documentation, context between clauses matters.

So the practical advice is: **don't treat the whole RFP as one type**. Split it by section type and apply different chunking strategies per section. This hybrid approach tends to outperform using a single chunk size across the entire document.

